[src:appimage/appimage] Released first in 2004 under the name klik, it was continuously developed, then renamed in 2011 to PortableLinuxApps and later in 2013 to AppImage.
[src:appimage/appimage] In 2015, Linus Torvalds, creator of the Linux kernel, said that "[t]his is just very cool.
[src:appimage/linux-distribution] A **Linux distribution**, often abbreviated as **distro**, is an operating system that includes the Linux kernel for its kernel functionality.
[src:appimage/linux-distribution] Although the name does not imply product distribution per se, a distro—if distributed on its own—is often obtained via a website intended specifically for the purpose.
[src:appimage/linux-distribution] Distros have been designed for a wide variety of systems ranging from personal computers (for example, Linux Mint and Zorin OS) to servers (for example, Red Hat Enterprise Linux) and from embedded devices (for example, OpenWrt) to supercomputers (for example, Rocks Cluster Distribution).
[src:appimage/linux-distribution] A distro typically includes many components in addition to the Linux kernel.
[src:appimage/linux-distribution] Commonly, it includes a package manager, an init system (such as systemd, OpenRC, SysVinit, or runit), GNU tools and libraries, documentation, IP network configuration utilities, the getty TTY setup program, and many more.
[src:appimage/linux-distribution] Typically, most of the included software is free and open-source software – made available both as binary for convenience and as source code to allow for modifying it.
[src:appimage/linux-distribution] A distro may also include proprietary software that is not available in source code form, such as a device driver binary.
[src:appimage/linux-distribution] A distro may be described as a particular assortment of application and utility software (various GNU tools and libraries, for example), packaged with the Linux kernel in such a way that its capabilities meet users' needs.
[src:appimage/linux-distribution] The software is usually adapted to the distribution and then combined into software packages by the distribution's maintainers.
[src:appimage/linux-distribution] The software packages are available online in repositories, which are storage locations usually distributed around the world.
[src:appimage/linux-distribution] Beside "glue" components, such as the distribution installers (for example, Debian-Installer and Anaconda) and the package management systems, very few packages are actually written by a distribution's maintainers.
[src:appimage/linux-distribution] Distributions have been designed for a wide range of computing environments, including desktops, servers, laptops, netbooks, mobile devices (phones and tablets), and embedded systems.
[src:appimage/linux-distribution] There are commercially backed distributions, such as Red Hat Enterprise Linux (Red Hat), openSUSE (SUSE) and Ubuntu (Canonical), and entirely community-driven distributions, such as Debian, Slackware, Gentoo and Arch Linux.
[src:appimage/linux-distribution] Most distributions come ready-to-use and prebuilt for a specific instruction set, while some (such as Gentoo) are distributed mostly in source code form and must be built before installation.
[src:appimage/linux-distribution] Linus Torvalds developed the Linux kernel and distributed its first version, 0.01, in 1991.
[src:appimage/linux-distribution] Linux was initially distributed as source code only, and later as a pair of downloadable floppy disk images: one bootable and containing the Linux kernel itself, and the other with a set of GNU utilities and tools for setting up a file system.
[src:appimage/linux-distribution] Since the installation procedure was complicated, especially in the face of growing amounts of available software, distributions sprang up to simplify it.
[src:appimage/linux-distribution] The two oldest, still active distribution projects started in 1993.
[src:appimage/linux-distribution] The SLS distribution was not well maintained, so in July 1993 a new SLS-based distribution, Slackware, was released by Patrick Volkerding.
[src:appimage/linux-distribution] Also dissatisfied with SLS, Ian Murdock set to create a free distribution by founding Debian in August 1993, with first public BETA released in January 1994 and first stable version in June 1996.
[src:appimage/linux-distribution] Users were attracted to Linux distributions as alternatives to MS-DOS compatible operating systems, Windows, Classic Mac OS, and proprietary versions of Unix.
[src:appimage/linux-distribution] Most early adopters were familiar with Unix from work or school.
[src:appimage/linux-distribution] They embraced Linux distributions for their low (or absent) cost, and the availability of the source code for most or all of their software.
[src:appimage/linux-distribution] As of 2025, Linux has become more popular in server and embedded devices markets than in the desktop market.
[src:appimage/linux-distribution] It is used in approximately 64.5% of web servers; its current operating system market share is about 2.51%, and its desktop operating system market share is about 2.94%.
[src:appimage/linux-distribution] Many Linux distributions provide an installation system akin to that provided with other modern operating systems.
[src:appimage/linux-distribution] Other distributions, including Gentoo Linux, provide only the binaries of a basic kernel, compilation tools, and an installer; the installer compiles all the requested software for the specific architecture of the user's computer, using these tools and the software's source code.
[src:appimage/linux-distribution] Distributions are normally segmented into *packages*.
[src:appimage/linux-distribution] Each package contains a specific application or service.
[src:appimage/linux-distribution] Examples of packages are a library for handling the PNG image format, a collection of fonts, and a web browser.
[src:appimage/linux-distribution] The package is typically provided as compiled code, with installation and removal of packages handled by a package management system (PMS) rather than a simple file archiver.
[src:appimage/linux-distribution] Each package intended for such a PMS contains meta-information such as its description, version number, and its dependencies (other packages it requires to run).
[src:appimage/linux-distribution] The package management system evaluates this meta-information to allow package searches, perform automatic upgrades to newer versions, and to check that all dependencies of a package are present (and either notify the user to install them, or install them automatically).
[src:appimage/linux-distribution] The package can also be provided as source code to be compiled on the system.
[src:appimage/linux-distribution] Most distributions install packages, including the kernel and other core operating system components, in a predetermined configuration.
[src:appimage/linux-distribution] A few now require or permit configuration adjustments at first install time.
[src:appimage/linux-distribution] This makes installation less daunting, particularly for new users, but is not always acceptable.
[src:appimage/linux-distribution] For specific requirements, much software must be carefully configured to be useful, to work correctly with other software, or to be secure, and local administrators are often obliged to spend time reviewing and reconfiguring it.
[src:appimage/linux-distribution] Some (but not all) distributions go to considerable lengths to adjust and customize the software they include, and some provide configuration tools to help users do so.
[src:appimage/linux-distribution] By obtaining and installing *everything* normally provided in a distribution, an administrator may create a "distribution less" installation.
[src:appimage/linux-distribution] It is possible to build such systems from scratch, avoiding distributions altogether.
[src:appimage/linux-distribution] One needs a way to generate the first binaries until the system is *self-hosting*.
[src:appimage/linux-distribution] This can be done via compilation on another system capable of building binaries for the intended target (possibly by cross-compilation).
[src:appimage/linux-distribution] The diversity of Linux distributions is due to technical, organizational, and philosophical variation among vendors and users.
[src:appimage/linux-distribution] The permissive licensing of free software means that users with sufficient knowledge and interest can customize any extant distribution, or design one to suit their own needs.
[src:appimage/linux-distribution] Rolling Linux distributions are kept current using small and frequent updates.
[src:appimage/linux-distribution] The terms *partially rolling* and *partly rolling* (along with synonyms *semi-rolling* and *half-rolling*), *fully rolling*, *truly rolling* and *optionally rolling* are sometimes used by software developers and users.
[src:appimage/linux-distribution] Repositories of **rolling distributions** usually contain very recent software releases—often the latest stable versions available.
[src:appimage/linux-distribution] They have pseudo-releases and installation media that are simply snapshots of the distribution at the time of the installation image's release.
[src:appimage/linux-distribution] Typically, a rolling-release OS installed from older installation medium can be fully updated after it is installed.
[src:appimage/linux-distribution] Depending on the usage case, there can be pros and cons to both standard release and rolling release software development methodologies.
[src:appimage/linux-distribution] In terms of the software development process, **standard releases** require significant development effort to keep old versions up-to-date by propagating bug fixes back to the newest branch, versus focusing on the newest development branch.
[src:appimage/linux-distribution] Also, unlike rolling releases, standard releases require more than one code branch to be developed and maintained, which increases the workload of the software developers and maintainers.
[src:appimage/linux-distribution] On the other hand, software features and technology planning are easier in standard releases due to a better understanding of upcoming features in the next version(s).
[src:appimage/linux-distribution] Software release cycles can also be synchronized with those of major upstream software projects, such as desktop environments.
[src:appimage/linux-distribution] As for the user experience, standard releases are often viewed as more stable and bug-free since software conflicts can be more easily addressed and the software stack more thoroughly tested and evaluated, during the software development cycle.
[src:appimage/linux-distribution] For this reason, they tend to be the preferred choice in enterprise environments and mission-critical tasks.
[src:appimage/linux-distribution] However, rolling releases offer more current software which can also provide increased stability and fewer software bugs along with the additional benefits of new features, greater functionality, faster running speeds, and improved system and application security.
[src:appimage/linux-distribution] Regarding software security, the rolling release model can have advantages in timely security updates, fixing system or application security bugs and vulnerabilities, that standard releases may have to wait till the next release for or patch in various versions.
[src:appimage/linux-distribution] In a rolling release distribution, where the user has chosen to run it as a highly dynamic system, the constant flux of software packages can introduce new unintended vulnerabilities.
[src:appimage/linux-distribution] A "live" distribution is a Linux distribution that can be booted from removable storage media such as optical discs or USB flash drives, instead of being installed on and booted from a hard disk drive.
[src:appimage/linux-distribution] The portability of installation-free distributions makes them advantageous for applications such as demonstrations, borrowing someone else's computer, rescue operations, or as installation media for a standard distribution.
[src:appimage/linux-distribution] When the operating system is booted from a read-only medium such as a CD or DVD, any user data that needs to be retained between sessions cannot be stored on the boot device but must be written to another storage device, such as a USB flash drive or a hard disk drive.
[src:appimage/linux-distribution] Many Linux distributions provide a "live" form in addition to their conventional form, which is a network-based or removable-media image intended to be used only for installation; such distributions include antiX, SUSE, Ubuntu, Linux Mint, MX Linux and Fedora Linux.
[src:appimage/linux-distribution] Some distributions, including Knoppix, Puppy Linux, Devil-Linux, SuperGamer, SliTaz GNU/Linux and dyne:bolic, are designed primarily for live use.
[src:appimage/linux-distribution] Additionally, some minimal distributions can be run directly from as little space as one floppy disk without the need to change the contents of the system's hard disk drive.
[src:appimage/linux-distribution] The website DistroWatch lists many Linux distributions and displays some of the ones that have the most web traffic on the site.
[src:appimage/linux-distribution] The Wikimedia Foundation released an analysis of the browser User Agents of visitors to WMF websites until 2015, which includes details of the most popular Operating System identifiers, including some Linux distributions.
[src:appimage/linux-distribution] Many of the popular distributions are listed below.
[src:appimage/linux-distribution] Whether such operating systems count as a "Linux distribution" is a controversial topic.
[src:appimage/linux-distribution] They use the Linux kernel, so the Linux Foundation and Chris DiBona, Google's former open-source chief, agree that Android is a Linux distribution; others, such as Google engineer Patrick Brady, disagree by noting the lack of support for many GNU tools in Android, including glibc.
[src:appimage/linux-distribution] Other Linux-kernel-based operating systems include Tizen, Mer/Sailfish OS, KaiOS and Amazon's Kindle firmware.
[src:appimage/linux-distribution] Lightweight Linux distributions are those that have been designed with support for older hardware in mind, allowing older hardware to still be used productively, or, for maximum possible speed in newer hardware by leaving more resources available for use by applications.
[src:appimage/linux-distribution] Examples include antiX, Damn Small Linux (based on antiX), Tiny Core Linux, Puppy Linux and Slitaz.
[src:appimage/linux-distribution] The Free Standards Group was an organization formed by major software and hardware vendors that aims to improve interoperability between different distributions.
[src:appimage/linux-distribution] Among their proposed standards are the Linux Standard Base, which defines a common ABI and packaging system for Linux, and the Filesystem Hierarchy Standard which recommends a standard file naming chart, notably the basic directory names found on the root of the tree of any Linux filesystem.
[src:appimage/linux-distribution] Those standards, however, see limited use, even among the distributions developed by members of the organization.
[src:appimage/linux-distribution] The diversity of Linux distributions means that not all software runs on all distributions, depending on what libraries and other system attributes are required.
[src:appimage/linux-distribution] Packaged software and software repositories are usually specific to a particular distribution, though cross-installation is sometimes possible on closely related distributions.
[src:appimage/linux-distribution] One of solutions for interdistribution issues, particularly to run software created for a distribution on another, is by using container such as Distrobox.
[src:appimage/linux-distribution] There are several ways to install a Linux distribution.
[src:appimage/linux-distribution] The most popular method of installing Linux is by booting from a live USB memory stick, which can be created by using a USB image writer application and the ISO image, which can be downloaded from various Linux distribution websites.
[src:appimage/linux-distribution] DVD disks, CD disks, network installations and even other hard drives can also be used as "installation media".
[src:appimage/linux-distribution] In the 1990s, Linux distributions were installed using sets of floppy disks, but this has been abandoned by all major distributions.
[src:appimage/linux-distribution] By the 2000s, many distributions offered CD and DVD sets with the vital packages on the first disk and less important packages on later ones.
[src:appimage/linux-distribution] Some distributions, such as Debian also enabled installing over a network after booting from either a set of floppy disks or a CD with only a small amount of data on it.
[src:appimage/linux-distribution] New users tend to begin by partitioning a hard drive to keep their formerly installed operating system.
[src:appimage/linux-distribution] The Linux distribution can then be installed on its own separate partition without affecting formerly saved data.
[src:appimage/linux-distribution] In a Live CD setup, the computer boots the entire operating system from CD without first installing it on the computer's hard disk.
[src:appimage/linux-distribution] Many distributions have a Live CD *installer*, where the computer boots the operating system from the disk, and it can then be installed on the computer's hard disk, providing a seamless transition from the OS running from the CD to the OS running from the hard disk.
[src:appimage/linux-distribution] Both servers and personal computers that come with Linux already installed are available from vendors including Hewlett-Packard, Dell and System76.
[src:appimage/linux-distribution] On embedded devices, Linux is typically held in the device's firmware and may or may not be consumer-accessible.
[src:appimage/linux-distribution] Anaconda, one of the more popular installers, is used by Red Hat Enterprise Linux, Fedora (which uses the Fedora Media Writer) and other distributions to simplify the installation process.
[src:appimage/linux-distribution] Debian, Ubuntu and many others use Debian-Installer.
[src:appimage/linux-distribution] The process of constantly switching between distributions is often referred to as "distro hopping".
[src:appimage/linux-distribution] Virtual machine software such as VirtualBox and VMware Workstation virtualize hardware allowing users to test live media on a virtual machine without installing to the real system.
[src:appimage/linux-distribution] Some websites like DistroWatch offer lists of distributions, and link to screenshots of operating systems as a way to get a first impression of various distributions.
[src:appimage/linux-distribution] Some distributions let the user install Linux on top of their current system, such as coLinux.
[src:appimage/linux-distribution] Linux is installed to the Windows hard disk partition, and can be started from inside Windows itself.
[src:appimage/linux-distribution] Virtual machines (such as VirtualBox or VMware Workstation) also make it possible for Linux to be run inside another OS.
[src:appimage/linux-distribution] The VM software simulates a separate computer onto which the Linux system is installed.
[src:appimage/linux-distribution] After installation, the virtual machine can be booted as if it were an independent computer.
[src:appimage/linux-distribution] Some specific proprietary software products are not available in any form for Linux.
[src:appimage/linux-distribution] As of September 2015, the Steam gaming service has over 1,500 games available on Linux, compared to 2,323 games for Mac and 6,500 Windows games.
[src:appimage/linux-distribution] Emulation and API-translation projects like Wine and CrossOver make it possible to run non-Linux-based software on Linux systems, either by emulating a proprietary operating system or by translating proprietary API calls (e.g., calls to Microsoft's Win32 or DirectX APIs) into native Linux API calls.
[src:appimage/linux-distribution] A virtual machine can also be used to run a proprietary OS (like Microsoft Windows) on top of Linux.
[src:appimage/linux-distribution] Pre-built computers are usually sold with an operating system other than Linux already installed by the original equipment manufacturer (OEM).
[src:appimage/linux-distribution] This limits Linux's market share: consumers are unaware that an alternative exists, they must make a conscious effort to use a different operating system, and they must either perform the actual installation themselves, or depend on support from a friend, relative, or computer professional.
[src:appimage/linux-distribution] However, it is possible to buy hardware with Linux already installed.
[src:appimage/linux-distribution] Lenovo, Hewlett-Packard, Dell, Affordy, Purism, Pine64 and System76 all sell general-purpose Linux laptops.
[src:appimage/linux-distribution] Custom-order PC manufacturers will also build Linux systems, but possibly with the Windows key on the keyboard.
[src:appimage/linux-distribution] Fixstars Solutions (formerly Terra Soft) sold Macintosh computers and PlayStation 3 consoles with Yellow Dog Linux installed.
[src:appimage/linux-distribution] It is more common to find embedded devices sold with Linux as the default manufacturer-supported OS, including the Linksys NSLU2 NAS device, TiVo's line of personal video recorders, and Linux-based cellphones (including Android smartphones), PDAs, and portable music players.
[src:appimage/linux-distribution] The current Microsoft Windows license lets the manufacturer determine the refund policy.
[src:appimage/linux-distribution] With prior versions of Windows, it was possible to obtain a refund if the manufacturer failed to provide the refund by litigation in the small claims courts.
[src:appimage/linux-distribution] On February 15, 1999, a group of Linux users in Orange County, California held a "Windows Refund Day" protest in an attempt to pressure Microsoft into issuing them refunds.
[src:appimage/linux-distribution] There are no official figures on the popularity, adoption, downloads or installed base of Linux distributions.
[src:appimage/linux-distribution] There are also no official figures for the total number of Linux systems, partly due to the difficulty of quantifying the number of PCs running Linux (see Desktop Linux adoption), since many users download Linux distributions.
[src:appimage/linux-distribution] Hence, the sales figures for Linux systems and commercial Linux distributions indicate a much lower number of Linux systems and level of Linux adoption than is the case; this is mainly due to Linux being free and open-source software that can be downloaded free of charge.
[src:appimage/linux-distribution] A Linux Counter Project had kept track of a running guesstimate of the number of Linux systems, but did not distinguish between rolling release and standard release distributions.
[src:appimage/linux-distribution] It ceased operation in August 2018, though a few related blog posts were created through October 2018.
[src:appimage/linux-distribution] Desktop usage statistical reports for particular Linux distributions have been collected and published since July 2014 by the Linux Hardware Project.
[src:appimage/linux-distribution] Statcounter, a web traffic analysis company, within the *operating system market share*, showed that the Linux operating systems had, according to them, 3.9% of the worldwide market share in July 2025.
[src:appimage/package-format] Packages may be converted from one type to another with software such as Alien.
[src:appimage/package-format] Packages are an important component in managing the security and integrity of the software supply chain.
[src:appimage/package-format] Packages containing executables and configuration can be digitally signed to establish the integrity of running software and protect against tampering.
[src:appimage/package-format] Package formats that support code signing include .deb (Debian), .msi (Microsoft Windows), .apk (Android) and .ipa (IOS, IPadOS).
[src:appimage/package-format] Arch Linux's Pacman and Slackware use 'tar' archives with generic naming but specific internal structures.
[src:appimage/portable-application] A **portable application** (**portable app**), sometimes also called standalone software, is a computer program designed to operate without changing other files or requiring other software to be installed.
[src:appimage/portable-application] In this way, it can be easily added to, run, and removed from any compatible computer without setup or side-effects.
[src:appimage/portable-application] In practical terms, a portable application often stores user-created data and configuration settings in the same directory it resides in.
[src:appimage/portable-application] This makes it easier to transfer the program with the user's preferences and data between different computers.
[src:appimage/portable-application] A program that doesn't have any configuration options can also be a portable application.
[src:appimage/portable-application] Portable applications can be stored on any data storage device, including internal mass storage, a file share, cloud storage or external storage such as USB drives, pen drives and floppy disks—storing its program files and any configuration information and data on the storage medium alone.
[src:appimage/portable-application] If no configuration information is required a portable program can be run from read-only storage such as CD-ROMs and DVD-ROMs.
[src:appimage/portable-application] Some applications are available in both installable and portable versions.
[src:appimage/portable-application] Some applications which are not portable by default do support optional portability through other mechanisms, the most common being command-line arguments.
[src:appimage/portable-application] Examples might include `/portable` to simply instruct the program to behave as a portable program, or `--cfg=/path/inifile` to specify the configuration file location.
[src:appimage/portable-application] Like any application, portable applications must be compatible with the computer system hardware and operating system.
[src:appimage/portable-application] Depending on the operating system, *portability* is more or less complex to implement; to operating systems such as AmigaOS, all applications are by definition portable.
[src:appimage/portable-application] Most portable applications do not leave files or settings on the host computer or modify the existing system and its configuration.
[src:appimage/portable-application] The application may not write to the Windows registry or store its configuration files (such as an INI file) in the user's profile, but today, many portables do; many, however, still store their configuration files in the portable directory.
[src:appimage/portable-application] Another possibility, since file paths will often differ on changing computers due to variation in drive letter assignments, is that portable applications may store them in a *relative* format.
[src:appimage/portable-application] While some applications have options to support this behavior, many programs are not designed to do this.
[src:appimage/portable-application] A common technique for such programs is the use of a launcher program to copy necessary settings and files to the host computer when the application starts and move them back to the application's directory when it closes.
[src:appimage/portable-application] This approach leaves the application itself unchanged, yet portable.
[src:appimage/portable-application] The same approach is used for individual application components: run-time libraries, COM components or ActiveX, not only for the entire application.
[src:appimage/portable-application] As a result, when individual components are ported in such manner they are able to be: integrated into original portable applications, repeatedly instantiated (virtually installed) with different configurations/settings on the same operating system (OS) without mutual conflicts.
[src:appimage/portable-application] As the ported components do not affect the OS-protected related entities (registry and files), the components will not require administrative privileges for installation and management.
[src:appimage/portable-application] Microsoft saw the need for an application-specific registry for its Windows operating system as far back as 2005.
[src:appimage/portable-application] It eventually incorporated some of this technology, using the techniques mentioned above, via its Application Compatibility Database using its Detours code library, into Windows XP.
[src:appimage/portable-application] It did not make any of this technology available via its system APIs.
[src:appimage/portable-application] Programs written with a Unix-like base in mind often do not make any assumptions.
[src:appimage/portable-application] Programs are therefore generally designed to use the `HOME` environment variable to store settings (e.g.
[src:appimage/portable-application] The dynamic linker provides an environment variable `LD_LIBRARY_PATH` that programs can use to load libraries from non-standard directories.
[src:appimage/portable-application] A Linux application without need for a user-interaction (e.g. adapting a script or environment variable) on varying directory paths can be achieved with the GCC linker option `$ORIGIN` which allows a relative library search path.
[src:appimage/portable-application] Not all programs honor this—some completely ignore $HOME and instead do a user look-up in `/etc/passwd` to find the home directory, therefore thwarting portability.
[src:appimage/portable-application] There are also cross-distro package formats that do not require admin rights to run, like Autopackage, AppImage, or CDE, but which gained only limited acceptance and support in the Linux community in the 2000s.
[src:appimage/portable-application] Around 2015 the idea of portable and distro independent packing for the Linux ecosystem got more traction when Linus Torvalds discussed this topic on the DebConf 2014 and endorsed later AppImage for his dive log application Subsurface.
[src:appimage/portable-application] For instance, MuseScore and Krita followed in 2016 and started to use AppImage builds for software deployment.
[src:appimage/portable-application] RedHat released in 2016 the Flatpak system, which is a successor of Alexander Larsson's *glick* project which was inspired by klik (now called AppImage).
[src:appimage/portable-application] Similarly, Canonical released in 2016 Snap packages for Ubuntu and many other Linux distros.
[src:appimage/portable-application] Many Mac applications that can be installed by drag-and-drop are inherently portable as Mac application bundles.
[src:appimage/portable-application] Examples include Mozilla Firefox, Skype and Google Chrome which do not require admin access and do not need to be placed into a central, restricted area.
[src:appimage/portable-application] Applications placed into `/Users/username/Applications` (`~/Applications`) are registered with macOS LaunchServices in the same way as applications placed into the main `/Applications` folder.
[src:appimage/portable-application] For example, right-clicking a file in Finder and then selecting "Open With..." will show applications available from both /Applications and ~/Applications.
[src:appimage/portable-application] Developers can create Mac product installers which allow the user to perform a home directory install, labelled "Install for me only" in the Installer user interface.
[src:appimage/portable-application] Such an installation is performed as the user.
[src:appimage/self-extracting-archive] A **self-extracting archive** (**SFX** or **SEA**) is a computer executable program which combines compressed data in an archive file with machine-executable code to extract the information.
[src:appimage/self-extracting-archive] Running on a compatible operating system, it does not need a suitable extractor in the target computer to extract the data.
[src:appimage/self-extracting-archive] The executable part of the file is known as a *decompressor stub*.
[src:appimage/self-extracting-archive] Self-extracting files are used to share compressed files with a party that may not have the software needed to decompress a regular archive.
[src:appimage/self-extracting-archive] Users can also use self-extracting archives to distribute their own software.
[src:appimage/self-extracting-archive] For example, the WinRAR installation program is made using the graphical GUI RAR self-extracting module Default.sfx.
[src:appimage/self-extracting-archive] Self-extracting archives contain an executable file module, which is used to run uncompressed files from compressed files.
[src:appimage/self-extracting-archive] The latter does not require an external program to decompress the contents of the self-extracting file and can run the operation itself.
[src:appimage/self-extracting-archive] However, file archivers like WinRAR can still treat a self-extracting file as if it were any other type of compressed file.
[src:appimage/self-extracting-archive] By using a file archiver, users can view or decompress self-extracting files they received without running executable code (for example, if they are concerned about viruses).
[src:appimage/self-extracting-archive] A self-extracting archive is extracted and stored on a disk when executed under an operating system that supports it.
[src:appimage/self-extracting-archive] Many embedded self-extractors support a number of command-line arguments, such as specifying the target location or selecting only specific files.
[src:appimage/self-extracting-archive] Unlike self-extracting archives, non-self-extracting archives only contain archived files and must be extracted with a program that is compatible with them.
[src:appimage/self-extracting-archive] While some formats of self-extracting archives cannot be extracted under another operating system, non-self-extracting ones can usually still be opened using a suitable extractor.
[src:appimage/self-extracting-archive] This tool will disregard the executable part of the file and extract only the archive resource.
[src:appimage/self-extracting-archive] The self-extracting executable may need to be renamed to contain a file extension associated with the corresponding packer; archive file formats known to support this include ARJ and ZIP.
[src:appimage/self-extracting-archive] Typically, self-extracting files for Microsoft operating systems such as DOS and Windows have a .exe extension, just like any other executable file.
[src:appimage/self-extracting-archive] For example, an archive may be called "somefiles.zip—it", which can be opened under any operating system by a suitable archive manager that supports both the file format and compression algorithm used.
[src:appimage/self-extracting-archive] It may also be converted into somefiles.exe, which will self-extract under Microsoft Windows.
[src:appimage/self-extracting-archive] It will not self-extract under Linux but can be opened with a suitable archive manager.
[src:appimage/self-extracting-archive] Files that are not recognized as archives by archive managers due to their executable extension can be renamed into .zip.
[src:appimage/self-extracting-archive] This works for ZIP archives due to the way the ZIP header is defined, but not necessarily for other less flexible archive formats.
[src:appimage/self-extracting-archive] There are several functionally equivalent but incompatible archive file formats, such as ZIP, RAR, 7z, and others.
[src:appimage/self-extracting-archive] Many programs can handle multiple types of archives, whereas others can create, extract, or modify only one type.
[src:appimage/self-extracting-archive] Additionally, there is a distinction between the file format and the compression algorithm.
[src:appimage/self-extracting-archive] A single file format, such as 7z, can support multiple different compression algorithms, including LZMA, LZMA2, PPMd, and BZip2.
[src:appimage/self-extracting-archive] Decompression utilities must be able to handle both the file format and the algorithm used when expanding self-extracting or standard archives.
[src:appimage/self-extracting-archive] Depending on the options used to create a self-extracting archive, the executable code placed at the beginning may vary.
[src:appimage/self-extracting-archive] When comparing a LZMA 7z archive to a LZMA2 7z archive, for example, the decompression routines will differ.
[src:appimage/self-extracting-archive] Several programs can create self-extracting archives.
[src:appimage/self-extracting-archive] Among the Windows archivers are WinZip, WinRAR, 7-Zip, WinUHA, KGB Archiver, Make SFX, the built-in IExpress wizard, and others, including experimental ones.
[src:appimage/self-extracting-archive] Macintosh users can choose among StuffIt, The Unarchiver, or 7z X as their archivers.
[src:appimage/self-extracting-archive] There are also programs that create self-extracting archives on Unix as shell scripts, which utilize programs like tar and gzip (which must be present in the destination system).
[src:appimage/self-extracting-archive] Others (like 7-Zip or RAR) can create self-extracting archives as regular executables in ELF format.
[src:appimage/self-extracting-archive] One of the early examples of self-extracting archives is the Unix shar archive, which combined a number of text files into a shell script that recreated their original content after being executed.
[src:appimage/self-extracting-archive] It is possible to archive both data and executable files with self-extracting archives.
[src:appimage/self-extracting-archive] It must be distinguished from executable compression, where the executable file only contains a single executable, and running the file does not result in the uncompressed file being stored on disk but in its code being executed in memory after decompression.
[src:appimage/self-extracting-archive] It reduces the size of files that aren't already efficiently compressed (most compression algorithms cannot reduce the size of already compressed files.
[src:appimage/self-extracting-archive] Compression usually reduces the size of plain text documents, but rarely affects JPEGs or word processor documents, as many modern word processors already involve a certain level of compression).
[src:appimage/self-extracting-archive] Self-extracting archives can also be used by users without the necessary programs for extracting their contents, as long as they run a compatible operating system.
[src:appimage/self-extracting-archive] A self-extracting archive may still be more convenient for users who do have archive management software.
[src:appimage/self-extracting-archive] As long as the underlying compression algorithm and format allow it, self-extracting archives can also be encrypted for security.
[src:appimage/self-extracting-archive] It is important to note, however, that in many cases, the file and directory names are not included in the encryption and can be viewed by anyone without a key or password.
[src:appimage/self-extracting-archive] If a person can guess part of the contents of the files from their names or context alone, an attacker may be able to break the encryption on the entire archive with a short amount of computing power and time.
[src:appimage/self-extracting-archive] Some systems for distributing files do not accept executable files in order to prevent the transmission of malicious programs.
[src:appimage/self-extracting-archive] These systems disallow self-extracting archive files unless they are cumbersomely renamed by the sender to, say, somefiles.exe, and later renamed back again by the recipient.
[src:appimage/self-extracting-archive] This technique is gradually becoming less effective, however, as an increasing number of security suites and antivirus software packages instead scan file headers for the underlying format rather than relying on a correct file extension.
[src:appimage/self-extracting-archive] Self-extracting archives will only run under the operating system family and platform with which they are compatible, making it more difficult to extract their contents under other systems.
[src:appimage/self-extracting-archive] Examples of self-extracting archives, which can be run on multiple targets (such as DOS and CP/M) rather than only the archive contents to be usable under multiple systems, are very rare, because they require the embedded decompressor stub to be a fat binary.
[src:appimage/self-extracting-archive] Since the self-extracting archives must include executable code to handle the extraction of the contained archive file, they are slightly larger in size than the original archive.
[src:appimage/software-deployment] Deployment can involve activities on the producer (software developer) side or on the consumer (user) side or both.
[src:appimage/software-deployment] Deployment to consumers is a hard task because the target systems are diverse and unpredictable.
[src:appimage/software-deployment] Software as a service avoids these difficulties by deploying only to dedicated servers that are typically under the producer's control.
[src:appimage/software-deployment] Because every software system is unique, the precise processes or procedures within each activity can hardly be defined.
[src:appimage/software-deployment] Therefore, "deployment" should be interpreted as a *general process* that has to be customized according to specific requirements or characteristics.
[src:appimage/software-deployment] When computers were extremely large, expensive, and bulky (mainframes and minicomputers), the software was often bundled together with the hardware by manufacturers and provided for free.
[src:appimage/software-deployment] A pivotal moment occurred in 1969 when IBM, influenced by antitrust lawsuits, began charging for software and services separately from hardware.
[src:appimage/software-deployment] This "unbundling" effectively created the modern software industry, turning software into a commercial product.
[src:appimage/software-deployment] Early deployment processes were highly structured; the Lincoln Labs Phased Model, developed in 1956 for the SAGE air defense system, introduced sequential phases that influenced later methodologies.
[src:appimage/software-deployment] This approach was formalized in the waterfall model, which became dominant after being described by Winston Royce in 1970.
[src:appimage/software-deployment] It led to infrequent, costly, and lengthy release cycles, often taking years.
[src:appimage/software-deployment] If business software needed to be installed, it often required an expensive, time-consuming visit by a systems architect or a consultant.
[src:appimage/software-deployment] For complex, on-premises installation of enterprise software today, this is sometimes still the case.
[src:appimage/software-deployment] The development of mass-market software for the new age of microcomputers in the 1980s brought new forms of software distribution – first cartridges, then Compact Cassettes, then floppy disks, and later (in the 1990s and beyond) optical media, the internet and flash drives.
[src:appimage/software-deployment] This shift meant that software deployment could be left to the customer.
[src:appimage/software-deployment] During this period, alternatives to the rigid waterfall model emerged.
[src:appimage/software-deployment] The Spiral Model, proposed by Barry Boehm in 1988, introduced a risk-driven, iterative approach that challenged waterfall's linear structure and paved the way for more flexible, agile methodologies.
[src:appimage/software-deployment] As customer-led deployment became standard, it was recognized that configuration should be user-friendly.
[src:appimage/software-deployment] In the 1990s, tools like InstallShield became popular, providing installer wizards that eliminated the need for users to perform complex tasks like editing registry entries.
[src:appimage/software-deployment] In pre-internet software deployments, releases were by nature expensive and infrequent affairs.
[src:appimage/software-deployment] The spread of the internet fundamentally transformed software distribution and made end-to-end agile software development viable by enabling rapid collaboration and digital delivery.
[src:appimage/software-deployment] The foundations for modern rapid deployment were laid in the 1990s when Kent Beck developed Continuous Integration as a core practice of Extreme Programming, advocating for developers to integrate their work daily.
[src:appimage/software-deployment] The advent of cloud computing and software as a service (SaaS) in the 2000s further accelerated this trend, allowing software to be deployed to a large number of customers in minutes.
[src:appimage/software-deployment] This shift also meant deployment schedules were now typically determined by the software supplier, not the customers.
[src:appimage/software-deployment] Such flexibility led to the rise of continuous delivery as a viable option, especially for web applications.
[src:appimage/software-deployment] Modern deployment strategies that build upon these principles include blue–green deployment and canary release deployment.
