[src:appimage/software-deployment] ), or even be gradually rolled out in parallel to different groups of customers, with the possibility of canceling one or more of the parallel deployments.
[src:appimage/software-deployment] Deactivation is the inverse of activation and refers to shutting down any already-executing components of a system.
[src:appimage/software-deployment] Deactivation is often required to perform other deployment activities, e.g., a software system may need to be deactivated before an update can be performed.
[src:appimage/software-deployment] Uninstallation is the inverse of installation.
[src:appimage/software-deployment] It is the removal of a system that is no longer required.
[src:appimage/software-deployment] The update process replaces an earlier version of all or part of a software system with a newer release.
[src:appimage/software-deployment] It commonly consists of deactivation followed by installation.
[src:appimage/software-deployment] , the old version of a software application is typically also uninstalled as an automatic part of the process.
[src:appimage/software-deployment] Automation of these update processes ranges from fully automatic to user-initiated and controlled.
[src:appimage/software-deployment] is an example of a system with a semi-automatic method for retrieving and installing updates to both the antivirus definitions and other components of the system.
[src:appimage/software-deployment] Other software products provide query mechanisms for determining when updates are available.
[src:appimage/software-deployment] Version tracking systems help the user find and install updates to software systems.
[src:appimage/software-deployment] For example: The Software Catalog stores the version and other information for each software package installed on a local system.
[src:appimage/software-deployment] One-click of a button launches a browser window to the upgrade web page for the application, including auto-filling of the user name and password for sites that require a login.
[src:appimage/software-deployment] so the process can be configured to be fully automated.
[src:appimage/software-deployment] Some third-party software also supports automated version tracking and upgrading for certain Windows software packages.
[src:appimage/software-deployment] The complexity and variability of software products have fostered the emergence of specialized roles for coordinating and engineering the deployment process.
[src:appimage/software-deployment] For desktop systems, end-users frequently also become the "software deployers" when they install a software package on their machine.
[src:appimage/software-deployment] The deployment of enterprise software involves many more roles, and those roles typically change as the application progresses from the test (pre-production) to production environments.
